                    </article>

                                                                                                </div>
                        

                        <p>Stepping outside of his role of advocacy director and into the shoes of a graduate student in the immunology department, Barclay said he found it personally troubling that 60 percent of the students affected by this reform are in science, technology, engineering and mathematics fields.&nbsp;</p>
<p>“We would never see a dime of that money. That is very simple and straightforward. Suffice it to say that it would be pretty devastating,” Barclay said.</p>
<p><strong>Moving forward</strong></p>
<p>This past Thursday, members in the Ways and Means Committee voted along party lines to advance the tax reform bill to the House floor. The Senate does not have a formal schedule for voting on its version.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Joglekar remarked that she does not envision any benefits for graduate students under the House bill.</p>
<p>“In fact, no one in higher education will benefit,” Joglekar said.</p>
